{"title_page": "2016 Wisconsin elections", "text_new": "{{Infobox election\n| election_name      = 2016 Wisconsin elections\n| country            = Wisconsin\n| type               = presidential\n| ongoing            = no\n| previous_election  = 2015 Wisconsin elections\n| previous_year      = 2015\n| next_election      = 2017 Wisconsin elections\n| next_year          = 2017\n}}\n{{ElectionsWI}}\nThe '''Wisconsin general elections, 2016''' were held in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Wisconsin]] on November 8, 2016.<ref>http://www.gab.wi.gov/sites/default/files/page/offices_to_be_elected_fall_2016_4_14_16_pdf_11538.pdf</ref> One of Wisconsin's [[U.S. Senate]] seats and all eight seats in the [[United States House of Representatives]] are up for election, as well as half of the [[Wisconsin Senate]] seats and all of the [[Wisconsin Assembly]] seats. [[Primary election]]s were held on August 9, 2016.<ref>http://www.gab.wi.gov/elections-voting/2016/fall-primary</ref>\n\nThe [[Wisconsin Republican Party]] made large gains in the 2016 election. Businessman and Republican presidential nominee [[Donald Trump]] won Wisconsin in an upset, becoming the first Republican to win the state since 1984.<ref name=\"BauerBuild\">{{cite web | last1=Bauer | first1=Scott | title=Republicans Build Majorities in Legislature | url=http://www.charlotteobserver.com/entertainment/tv/article113209848.html | date=November 9, 2016 | publisher=[[The Charlotte Observer]] (from the [[Associated Press]]) | accessdate=November 25, 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161110142546/http://www.charlotteobserver.com/entertainment/tv/article113209848.html | archive-date=November 10, 2016 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Kueppers | first1=Courtney | title=Trump Becomes First Republican Presidential Candidate Since 1984 To Win Wisconsin | url=http://www.wpr.org/trump-becomes-1st-republican-presidential-candidate-1984-win-wisconsin | date=November 8, 2016 | publisher=[[Wisconsin Public Radio]] | accessdate=November 25, 2016}}</ref> Additionally, the state GOP had a strong showing in the [[Wisconsin Legislature|State Legislature]], building their largest majorities since 1957,<ref name=\"BauerBuild\"/><ref>{{cite web | last1=Marley | first1=Patrick | last2=Stein | first2=Jason | title=GOP Strengthens Hold on Legislature | url=http://www.sheboyganpress.com/story/news/politics/elections/2016/11/08/gop-retains-hold-legislature/93163322/ | date=November 9, 2016 | publisher=[[Sheboygan Press]] | accessdate=November 25, 2016}}</ref> and Republican Senator [[Ron Johnson (Wisconsin politician)|Ron Johnson]] defeated [[Russ Feingold]] a second time for a second term.<ref name=\"BauerBuild\"/><ref>{{cite web | last1=Schleifer | first1=Theodore | title=Ron Johnson Earns Surprise GOP Win in Wisconsin Senate Race | url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/11/08/politics/ron-johnson-russ-feingold-wisconsin-senate-election-results/ | date=November 8, 2016 | publisher=[[CNN]] | accessdate=November 25, 2016}}</ref> This put Walker and the Wisconsin GOP in a strong position.<ref>{{cite web | last1=Litke | first1=Eric | title=5 Wisconsin Winners in Trump Tidal Wave | url=http://www.postcrescent.com/story/news/politics/elections/2016/11/10/5-wisconsin-winners-trump-tidal-wave/93550526/ | date=November 10, 2016 | publisher=[[The Post-Crescent]] | accessdate=November 25, 2016}}</ref>  \n\nWisconsin Republicans also celebrated the victory of Justice [[Rebecca Bradley (judge)|Rebecca Bradley]] in the April election for [[Wisconsin Supreme Court]].  Bradley had been appointed to the court in 2015 after the death of Justice [[N. Patrick Crooks]], who had been seen as a swing vote on the court.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://madison.com/wsj/news/local/govt-and-politics/scott-walker-appoints-rebecca-bradley-to-supreme-court/article_36075f31-6912-59cc-bdc5-3c84bfaa3106.html |title= Scott Walker appoints Rebecca Bradley to Supreme Court  |date= October 10, 2015 |accessdate= April 18, 2020 | last= DeFour |first= Matthew |newspaper= [[Wisconsin State Journal]] }}</ref>\n\n==Federal==\n===President===\n{{Main|United States presidential election in Wisconsin, 2016}}\n\n===Senate===\n{{Main|United States Senate election in Wisconsin, 2016}}\nIn a rematch of the [[United States Senate election in Wisconsin, 2010|2010 election]], first term incumbent Republican [[Ron Johnson (Wisconsin politician)|Ron Johnson]] ran against former Democratic U.S. Senator [[Russ Feingold]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wuwm.com/post/candidates-ramp-rhetoric-wisconsin-senate-race|title=Candidates Ramp up the Rhetoric in Wisconsin Senate Race|date=July 5, 2016|work=[[WUWM]]|last=Mikkelson|first=Marti}}</ref> Johnson defeated Feingold in the general election with 50.2% of the vote.<ref name=\"Generalelection\">{{cite web|url=http://elections.wi.gov/sites/default/files/County%20by%20County%20Report-US%20Senate.pdf |title=2016 General Election |publisher=State of Wisconsin |date=November 8, 2016 |accessdate=December 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===House of Representatives===\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in Wisconsin, 2016}}\nAll of Wisconsin's eight [[United States House of Representatives]] seats were up for election in 2016. Party composition remained unchanged after the general election.\n\n==State==\n===Legislature===\n====State Senate====\n{{Main|2016 Wisconsin State Senate election}}\nThe 16 even-numbered districts out of 33 seats in the [[Wisconsin Senate]] were up for election in 2016. Nine of these seats were held by Republicans and seven were held by Democrats. Prior to the election, Republicans controlled the chamber with a 19 to 14 majority, but they gained a seat in the election.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n\n|- valign=bottom\n! colspan=1 | Senatorial district\n! colspan=3 | Incumbent\n! colspan=2 | This race\n! colspan=4 | Results\n|- valign=bottom\n! District\n! Senator\n! Party\n! First<br/>elected\n! Incumbent Status\n! Candidates<ref name=list>{{cite news|title=Candidate List for the August 9, 2016 Primary Election|url=http://www.gab.wi.gov/sites/default/files/page/candidates_on_ballot_aug_9_partisan_primary_after_20612.pdf|accessdate=July 12, 2016|newspaper=Wisconsin Government Accountability Board}}</ref>\n!Winner<ref>{{cite web|url=http://elections.wi.gov/sites/default/files/County%20by%20County%20Report-State%20Senate.pdf |title=County by County Report - State Senate |publisher=Wisconsin Elections Commission |date=November 29, 2016 |accessdate=December 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\n|-\n! [[Wisconsin Senate, District 2|2]]\n| [[Robert Cowles]]\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} | Republican\n| 1987\n| Running\t\n| Robert Cowles (Republican)<br>John Powers (Democratic)\n| {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''Robert Cowles'''<br>65%\n|-\n! [[Wisconsin Senate, District 4|4]]\n| [[Lena Taylor]]\n| {{Party shading/Democratic}} | Democrat\n| 2005\n| Running\n| Lena Taylor (Democrat)\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''Lena Taylor'''<br>100%\n|-\n! [[Wisconsin Senate, District 6|6]]\n| [[Nikiya Harris]]\n| {{Party shading/Democratic}} | Democrat\n| 2013\n| Not Running\t\n| LaTonya Johnson (Democrat)\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''LaTonya Johnson'''<br>100%\n|-\n! [[Wisconsin Senate, District 8|8]]\n| [[Alberta Darling]]\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} | Republican\n| 1993\n| Running\n| Alberta Darling (Republican)\n|{{Party shading/Republican}}|'''Alberta Darling'''<br>100%\n|-\n! [[Wisconsin Senate, District 10|10]]\n| [[Sheila Harsdorf]]\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} | Republican\n| 2001\n| Running\n| Sheila Harsdorf (Republican)<br>Diane Odeen (Democrat)\n|{{Party shading/Republican}}|'''Sheila Harsdorf'''<br>63%\n|-\n! [[Wisconsin Senate, District 12|12]]\n| [[Tom Tiffany]]\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} | Republican\n| 2013\n| Running\n| Tom Tiffany (Republican)<br>Bryan Van Stippen (Democrat)\n|{{Party shading/Republican}}|'''Tom Tiffany'''<br>63%\n|-\n! [[Wisconsin Senate, District 14|14]]\n| [[Luther Olsen]]\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} | Republican\n| 2004\n| Running\t\n| Luther Olsen (Republican)<br>Brian Smith (Democrat)\n|{{Party shading/Republican}}|'''Luther Olsen'''<br>57%\n|-\n! [[Wisconsin Senate, District 16|16]]\n| [[Mark F. Miller]]\n| {{Party shading/Democratic}} | Democrat\n| 2005\n| Running\n| Mark Miller (Democrat)\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''Mark Miller'''<br>100%\n|-\n! [[Wisconsin Senate, District 18|18]]\n| [[Rick Gudex]]\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} | Republican\n| 2013\n| Not Running\n| Dan Feyen (Republican)<br>Mark Harris (Democrat)\n|{{Party shading/Republican}}|'''Dan Feyen'''<br>56%\n|-\n! [[Wisconsin Senate, District 20|20]]\n| [[Duey Stroebel]]\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} | Republican\n| 2015\n| Running\t\n| Duey Stroebel (Republican)\n|{{Party shading/Republican}}|'''Duey Stroebel'''<br>100%\n|-\n! [[Wisconsin Senate, District 22|22]]\n| [[Robert Wirch]]\n| {{Party shading/Democratic}} | Democrat\n| 1997\n| Running\t\n| Robert Wirch (Democrat)\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''Robert Wirch'''<br>100%\n|-\n! [[Wisconsin Senate, District 24|24]]\n| [[Julie Lassa]]\n| {{Party shading/Democratic}} | Democrat\n| 2003\n| Running \n| Patrick Testin (Republican)<br>Julie Lassa (Democrat)\n|{{Party shading/Republican}}|'''Patrick Testin'''<br>52%\n|-\n! [[Wisconsin Senate, District 26|26]]\n| [[Fred Risser]]\n| {{Party shading/Democratic}} | Democrat\n| 1962\n| Running\n| Fred Risser (Democrat)\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''Fred Risser'''<br>100%\n|-\n! [[Wisconsin Senate, District 28|28]]\n| [[Mary Lazich]]\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} | Republican\n| 1998\n| Not Running \n| Dave Craig (Republican)\n|{{Party shading/Republican}}|'''Dave Craig'''<br>100%\n|-\n! [[Wisconsin Senate, District 30|30]]\n| [[Dave Hansen]]\n| {{Party shading/Democratic}} | Democrat\n| 2001\n| Running\t\n| Dave Hansen (Democratic)<br>Eric Wimberger (Republican)\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''Dave Hansen'''<br>51%\n|-\n! [[Wisconsin Senate, District 32|32]]\n| [[Jennifer Shilling]]\n| {{Party shading/Democratic}} | Democrat\n| 2011\n| Running\n| Jennifer Shilling (Democrat)<br>[[Dan Kapanke]] (Republican)<br>Chip DeNure (Independent)\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''Jennifer Shilling'''<br>49%\n|}\n\n====State Assembly====\n{{Main|2016 Wisconsin State Assembly election}}\nAll 99 seats of the [[Wisconsin State Assembly]] were up for election in November. Nine Assemblymen (6 Republicans, 3 Democrats) did not seek re-election.<ref name=list/>\n\n{|class=wikitable style=\"text-align:center\"\n|- style=\"vertical-align:bottom;\"\n!rowspan=3|Affiliation\n!colspan=2|Party <div style=\"font-size:80%\">(Shading indicates majority caucus)</div>\n!rowspan=3|Total\n!\n|- style=\"height:5px\"\n| style=\"background-color:{{Republican Party (United States)/meta/color}}\" |\n| style=\"background-color:{{Democratic Party (United States)/meta/color}}\" |\n| style=\"background-color:black\" |\n|-\n![[Wisconsin Republican Party|Republican]]\n![[Wisconsin Democratic Party|Democratic]]\n!Vacant\n|-\n!nowrap style=\"font-size:80%\"| Before 2016 elections\n|{{party shading/Republican}}|63\n|36\n! 99\n|0\n|-\n!nowrap style=\"font-size:80%\"|Latest voting share \n!{{party shading/Republican}}|{{percentage|63|99}}\n!|{{percentage|36|99}}\n!colspan=2|\n|-\n|colspan=5|\n|-\n!nowrap style=\"font-size:80%\"| After 2016 elections\n|{{party shading/Republican}}|64\n|35\n! 99\n|0\n|-\n!nowrap style=\"font-size:80%\"|Latest voting share \n!{{party shading/Republican}}|{{percentage|64|99}}\n!|{{percentage|35|99}}\n!colspan=2|\n|}\n\n===Judiciary===\n\n====State Supreme Court====\nIncumbent [[Wisconsin Supreme Court]] Justice [[Rebecca Bradley (judge)|Rebecca Bradley]] defeated Judge [[JoAnne Kloppenburg]] of the Wisconsin Court of Appeals in the April general election.  Justice Bradley had been appointed to the court in 2015 by Governor [[Scott Walker (politician)|Scott Walker]], to replace Justice [[N. Patrick Crooks]], who had died in office.  Justice Crooks' term was already set to expire in 2016, thus no special election needed to be scheduled.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://madison.com/wsj/news/local/govt-and-politics/rebecca-bradley-elected-to-state-supreme-court/article_c9f0b565-3199-5b0d-b605-5334c9ac1203.html |title= Rebecca Bradley elected to state Supreme Court  |date= April 6, 2016 |accessdate= April 18, 2020 |newspaper= [[Wisconsin State Journal]] |last= Beck |first= Molly }}</ref>\n\nMilwaukee County Circuit Court Judge [[Joe Donald|M. Joseph \"Joe\" Donald]] was also a candidate in this election, but did not advance from the February primary election.\n\nThough Wisconsin judicial elections are nonpartisan, Justice Bradley's victory was seen as an important win for the Republican party, as she claims a judicial philosophy aligned with conservative judges like [[Samuel Alito]] and [[Clarence Thomas]], and she had been endorsed by Republican-aligned interest groups such as the [[National Rifle Association]] and Wisconsin Right to Life.<ref>{{cite press release|url= http://www.thewheelerreport.com/wheeler_docs/files/0329nra.pdf |title= NRA Endorses Wisconsin Supreme Court Justice Rebecca Bradley |via= [[The Wheeler Report]] |date= March 29, 2016 |accessdate= April 18, 2020 |publisher= [[National Rifle Association]] |location = [[Fairfax, Virginia]] }}</ref>  Justice Crooks, who she was replacing, was seen as a swing vote on the court, so this was a net gain for the conservative bloc on the court.\n{{Election box begin | title=Wisconsin Supreme Court Election, 2016<ref>{{cite report|url=https://docs.legis.wisconsin.gov/misc/lrb/blue_book/2017_2018 |title=Wisconsin Blue Book 2017-2018 |year=2017 |publisher= State of Wisconsin |location=[[Madison, Wisconsin]] |accessdate= January 1, 2020 |chapter= Elections Results | pages= 508, 511}}</ref>}}\n| colspan=\"6\" style=\"text-align:center;background-color: #e9e9e9;\"| '''Primary Election, February 16, 2016'''\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Nonpartisan\n  |candidate  = [[Rebecca Bradley (judge)|Rebecca Bradley]] (incumbent)\n  |votes      = 251,823\n  |percentage = 44.61%\n  |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Nonpartisan\n  |candidate  = [[JoAnne Kloppenburg]]\n  |votes      = 243,190\n  |percentage = 43.16%\n  |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Nonpartisan\n  |candidate  = [[Joe Donald|M. Joseph Donald]]\n  |votes      = 68,373\n  |percentage = 12.12%\n  |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = \n  |candidate  = ''Scattering''\n  |votes      = 631\n  |percentage = 0.11%\n  |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box total\n  |votes      = '''567,038'''\n  |percentage = '''100.0%'''\n  |change     =\n}}\n| colspan=\"6\" style=\"text-align:center;background-color: #e9e9e9;\"| '''General Election, April 5, 2016'''\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Nonpartisan\n  |candidate  = [[Rebecca Bradley (judge)|Rebecca Bradley]] (incumbent)\n  |votes      = 1,020,092\n  |percentage = 52.23%\n  |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Nonpartisan\n  |candidate  = [[JoAnne Kloppenburg]]\n  |votes      = 928,377\n  |percentage = 47.53%\n  |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = \n  |candidate  = ''Scattering''\n  |votes      = 4,678\n  |percentage = 0.24%\n  |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box total\n  |votes      = '''1,953,147'''\n  |percentage = '''100.0%'''\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n====State Court of Appeals====\nAll four districts of the [[Wisconsin Court of Appeals]] had a seat up for election in 2016.  None of the races were contested.\n* In District I, Judge [[Joan F. Kessler]] was elected to her third term without opposition.\n* In District II, Judge [[Paul F. Reilly]] was elected to his second term without opposition.\n* In District III, Judge [[Thomas Hruz]] was elected to his first full term, after being appointed to the court by Governor [[Scott Walker (politician)|Scott Walker]] in 2014.\n* In District IV, Judge [[Brian Blanchard]] was elected to his second term without opposition.\n\n====State Circuit Courts====\nForty of the state's 249 [[Wisconsin circuit courts|circuit court]] seats were up for election in 2020.  Ten of those seats were contested.  Three incumbent judges were defeated&mdash;Milwaukee County judges Paul Rifelj and Michelle Ackerman Havas, and Eau Claire County judge Brian H. Wright.  All three defeated judges had been appointed by Governor [[Scott Walker (politician)|Scott Walker]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Circuit\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Branch\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Incumbent\n! colspan=\"3\" |Elected\n! colspan=\"3\" |Defeated\n! Defeated in Primary\n|-\n!Name\n!Votes\n!%\n!Name\n!Votes\n!%\n!Name(s)\n|-\n! Barron\n| 1\n| James C. Babler\n| '''James C. Babler'''\n| align=\"right\"| 12,364\n| align=\"right\"| 99.66%\n| colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" | \n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Crawford\n| James P. Czajkowski\n| '''Lynn Marie Rider'''\n| align=\"right\"| 4,327\n| align=\"right\"| 99.63%\n| colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" | \n|-\n! rowspan=\"6\" | Dane\n| 3\n| Jim Troupis\n| '''Valerie L. Bailey-Rihn'''\n| align=\"right\"| 132,270\n| align=\"right\"| 99.10%\n| colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" | \n|-\n| 4\n| Amy Smith\n| '''Everett Mitchell'''\n| align=\"right\"| 132,939\n| align=\"right\"| 99.14%\n| colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" | \n|-\n| 5\n| Nicholas J. McNamara\n| '''Nicholas J. McNamara'''\n| align=\"right\"| 131,068\n| align=\"right\"| 99.19%\n| colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" | \n|-\n| 14\n| C. William Foust\n| '''John D. Hyland'''\n| align=\"right\"| 130,198\n| align=\"right\"| 99.23%\n| colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" | \n|-\n| 15\n| Stephen Ehlke\n| '''Stephen Ehlke'''\n| align=\"right\"| 130,754\n| align=\"right\"| 99.27%\n| colspan=\"4\" align=\"cent