[Milwaukee mayoral election, 2016|was re-elected]] to his fourth term as [[List of mayors of Milwaukee|Mayor]] of [[Milwaukee]], defeating alderman Bob Donovan.\n* [[List of Milwaukee County executives|County Executive]] [[Chris Abele]] was re-elected, defeating state senator [[Chris Larson]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{United States elections, 2016}}\n\n[[Category:2016 Wisconsin elections| ]]\n[[Category:Wisconsin State Legislature elections]]\n", "name_user": "Asdasdasdff", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eState Supreme Court", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2016_Wisconsin_elections"}
{"title_page": "Eoin McNamee (Irish republican)", "text_new": "{{about|the Irish Republican|the writer|Eoin McNamee}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name          = Eoin McNamee\n| image         = Eoin McNamee.jpg\n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_date    = \n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = 9 August 1986\n| death_place   = \n| relatives     = \n| years_active  = \n| office2       = [[List of Irish Republican Army chiefs of staff|Chief of Staff of the IRA]]\n| term_start2   = {{Circa}} March 1942\n| term_end2     = {{Circa}} May 1942\n| predecessor2  = [[Se\u00e1n McCool]]\n| successor2    = [[Hugh McAteer]]\n| branch        = [[Irish Republican Army (1922\u20131969)]]\n| rank          = \n| battles       = [[S-Plan]]\n}}\n\n'''Eoin McNamee ''' (??? - 9 August 1986) was an Irish Republican and former [[Chief of Staff of the Irish Republican Army]].\n\n==Background==\nMcNamee is described as having grown up \"in the [[Sperrins|Sperrin Mountains]]\" of [[County Tyrone]] and [[County Londonderry]] in present day [[Northern Ireland]], and received little in the way of formal education.\u201cA scholarly, astute, and sane man, with clear perception he saw that a successful revolutionary effort had to be fought on all levels, including political and agitation, but he remained totally committed to the view that armed struggle was the cutting edge or the spear of efforts, the key to victory.\u201d  <ref name=\"IrishCentral\">{{cite web |url=https://www.irishcentral.com/roots/history/eoin-mcnamee-ira |title=The IRA Chief of Staff who was \"unbought, unconquered, and unpurchasable to the last\" |last=Hegarty-Thorne |first=Kathleen |date=25 July 2019 |website=IrishCentral.com |publisher= |access-date=27 November 2019 |quote=}}</ref>\n\n==Irish Republican Army==\nHe joined the [[Irish Republican Army (1922-1969)|Irish Republican Army]] in 1932 [[Greencastle, County Tyrone|Greencastle]], County Tyrone before emigrating to [[London]]. He was involved in the [[Republican Congress]], an attempt by the far-left in Ireland to form a political party that would be on good terms with the IRA. However, the Republican Congress split between having moderate Republican goals or an explicitly Communist outlook.<ref name=\"IrishCentral\"/>\n\nBetween 1937 and 1939 he lived in England, still operating for the IRA, working as an \"intelligence officer\". In March and April 1938 he attended IRA conventions in Ireland and was the spokesman for [[Se\u00e1n Russell|Se\u00e1n Russell's]] faction in the voting for a new Chief of Staff. During this time period he, along with other IRA members who were operating in England, was also given a brief introduction into how to create explosives by [[Seamus O'Donovan]] and Paddy McGrath as an obvious forerunner to the [[S-Plan]]. The [[S-Plan]] was a bombing campaign carried out by the IRA against targets in [[Great Britain]] during wartime.<ref name=\"IrishCentral\"/>\n\nMcNamee was recalled to Ireland in April 1939 and by 11 June 1939 he was charged with being a member of the I.R.A. and sentenced to six months in Crumlin Road Jail, Belfast.<ref>Coogan, Tim: The IRA A History. Rinehart Publishers (1993), pg131.</ref> He was released in May 1940 and he returned to Tyrone where he became a leadership figure. In March 1942 IRA Chief of Staff [[Se\u00e1n McCool]] was arrested and imprisoned, and that point the job came to McNamee.<ref name=\"IrishCentral\"/>\n\nHe didn't hold the position long holder, as he was later arrested again, this time in [[Dublin]] on 23 May 1942. He was given a three-year sentence to be served in the [[Curragh]], where he was placed with hundreds of other men from across Ireland who had been arrested for IRA activity by a [[Fianna F\u00e1il]] government determined not to allow the IRA to threaten Ireland's neutrality. During his him in the Curragh he learned [[Gaeilge|Irish]] and [[Spanish language|Spanish]], while he raised the eyebrows of some detainees when he described [[Jesus Christ]] as \"as a revolutionary and a socialist\".<ref name=\"IrishCentral\"/>  It was also during this period that he is believed to have become a [[Trotskyist]] upon conversations with fellow left-wing IRA members in the camp.<ref>{{cite book |last=Bell |first=J. Bowyer |date=1987 |title=The Gun in Politics: Analysis of Irish Political Conflict, 1916-86  |url=https://books.google.ie/books?id=DyEuDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT116&lpg=PT116&dq=Eoin+McNamee+IRA+Trotskyist&source=bl&ots=xOanGYed5s&sig=ACfU3U1twaZve4dhl03Pt-a39wVgMwrqsw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiDoOaCxonmAhUlQRUIHZeUAwgQ6AEwDXoECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=Eoin%20McNamee%20IRA%20Trotskyist&f=false |location= |publisher=Routledge |page= |isbn= |author-link= |quote=Inside the Curragh, Gould not only offered Russian Language classes to the bored but also the ideological temptations of communism. And he began to have some takers and, given the Curragh, some dissenters as ultimately the Trotskyists, including Eoin McNamee (...) outnumbered the Stalinists. Somehow to them Trotsky seemed more anti-imperialist than Stalin.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Treacy |first=Matt |date=2013 |title=The Communist Party of Ireland 1921 - 2011 |url=https://books.google.ie/books?id=DpT2AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA161&lpg=PA161&dq=Eoin+McNamee+IRA+Trotskyist&source=bl&ots=ua6k9y8lF5&sig=ACfU3U1jRhguQRY1VSpQHG1fSYqFs_2REQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiDoOaCxonmAhUlQRUIHZeUAwgQ6AEwDnoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=Eoin%20McNamee%20IRA%20Trotskyist&f=false |location= |publisher= |page=161 |isbn= |author-link= |quote=Boywer Bell claims that Eoin McNamee became a Trotskyist in the Curragh}}</ref>\n\n==Later life==\nFollowing the years spent in the Curragh, McNamee emigrated to the [[United States]]. He moved first to Philadelphia before settling in the Chicago area, where he is supposed to have acted as the go-between for the IRA leadership and its weapons suppliers in the U.S. When the IRA split between [[Official IRA]] and the [[Provisional IRA]] he choose to side with the Provisionals. He was said to be a close friend of fellow IRA gun-runner and left-winger [[George Harrison (Irish Republican)|George Harrison]]. McNamee was another Irish man who took no time away from Army duties to marry. Even after he had established himself in the United States, first in Philadelphia and finally in Chicago, he surrounded himself not with children and toys but with fellow Irishmen and women whose devotion to Ireland\u2019s full freedom equalled his own. He had joined the IRA in 1932 and remained a faithful son until his last breath. <ref>{{cite web|last1=Holland|first1=John|title=IRA Puts On A Hard Face|url=http://irishecho.com/2011/02/ira-puts-on-a-hard-face-4/|website=irishecho.com|publisher=irish echo newspaper, Feb 16, 2014|accessdate=19 November 2014|ref=1}}</ref><ref name=\"IrishCentral\"/>\n\nA Sinn F\u00e9in [[cumann]] is named in his honor: Eoin McNamee Cumann, Kildress, Co. Tyrone. A monument to his memory stands at a quiet crossroad in the Sperrin Mountains of his native County Tyrone.\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book|last=English|first=Richard|title=Armed Struggle: The History of the IRA|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K-XsIheKNYIC&pg=PA62|accessdate=29 December 2014|date=2008-09-04|publisher=Pan Macmillan|isbn=9780330475785|pages=62\u2013}}\n*{{cite book|last=Bell|first=J. Bowyer|title=The Gun in Politics: An Analysis of Irish Political Conflict, 1916-1986|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_qQsuhGKDzoC&pg=PA102|accessdate=29 December 2014|date=1987-01-01|publisher=Transaction Publishers|isbn=9781412837132|pages=102\u2013}}\n*{{cite book|last=Treacy|first=Matt|title=The Communist Party of Ireland 1921 - 2011|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DpT2AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA161|accessdate=29 December 2014|year=2012|publisher=Lulu.com|isbn=9781291093186|pages=161\u2013}}\n*{{cite book|last=Hull|first=Mark M.|title=Irish Secrets: German Espionage in Ireland, 1939-45|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wjFnAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=29 December 2014|date=January 2003|publisher=Irish Academic Press|isbn=9780716527565}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{ATIRA}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McNamee, Eoin}}\n[[Category:1986 deaths]]\n[[Category:Irish nationalists]]\n[[Category:Irish republicans]]\n[[Category:Irish Trotskyists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the Irish Republican|the writer|Eoin McNamee}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name          = Eoin McNamee\n| image         = Eoin McNamee.jpg\n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_date    = \n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = 9 August 1986\n| death_place   = \n| relatives     = \n| years_active  = \n| office2       = [[List of Irish Republican Army chiefs of staff|Chief of Staff of the IRA]]\n| term_start2   = {{Circa}} March 1942\n| term_end2     = {{Circa}} May 1942\n| predecessor2  = [[Se\u00e1n McCool]]\n| successor2    = [[Hugh McAteer]]\n| branch        = [[Irish Republican Army (1922\u20131969)]]\n| rank          = \n| battles       = [[S-Plan]]\n}}\n\n'''Eoin McNamee ''' (??? - 9 August 1986) was an Irish Republican and former [[Chief of Staff of the Irish Republican Army]].\n\n==Background==\nMcNamee is described as having grown up \"in the [[Sperrins|Sperrin Mountains]]\" of [[County Tyrone]] and [[County Londonderry]] in present day [[Northern Ireland]], and received little in the way of formal education.\u201cA scholarly, astute, and sane man, with clear perception he saw that a successful revolutionary effort had to be fought on all levels, including political and agitation, but he remained totally committed to the view that armed struggle was the cutting edge or the spear of efforts, the key to victory.\u201d  <ref name=\"IrishCentral\">{{cite web |url=https://www.irishcentral.com/roots/history/eoin-mcnamee-ira |title=The IRA Chief of Staff who was \"unbought, unconquered, and unpurchasable to the last\" |last=Hegarty-Thorne |first=Kathleen |date=25 July 2019 |website=IrishCentral.com |publisher= |access-date=27 November 2019 |quote=}}</ref>\n\n==Irish Republican Army==\nHe joined the [[Irish Republican Army (1922-1969)|Irish Republican Army]] in 1932 [[Greencastle, County Tyrone|Greencastle]], County Tyrone before emigrating to [[London]]. He was involved in the [[Republican Congress]], an attempt by the far-left in Ireland to form a political party that would be on good terms with the IRA. However, the Republican Congress split between having moderate Republican goals or an explicitly Communist outlook.<ref name=\"IrishCentral\"/>\n\nBetween 1937 and 1939 he lived in England, still operating for the IRA, working as an \"intelligence officer\". In March and April 1938 he attended IRA conventions in Ireland and was the spokesman for [[Se\u00e1n Russell|Se\u00e1n Russell's]] faction in the voting for a new Chief of Staff. During this time period he, along with other IRA members who were operating in England, was also given a brief introduction into how to create explosives by [[Seamus O'Donovan]] and Paddy McGrath as an obvious forerunner to the [[S-Plan]]. The [[S-Plan]] was a bombing campaign carried out by the IRA against targets in [[Great Britain]] during wartime.<ref name=\"IrishCentral\"/>\n\nMcNamee was recalled to Ireland in April 1939 and by 11 June 1939 he was charged with being a member of the I.R.A. and sentenced to six months in Crumlin Road Jail, Belfast.<ref>Coogan, Tim: The IRA A History. Rinehart Publishers (1993), pg131.</ref> He was released in May 1940 and he returned to Tyrone where he became a leadership figure. In March 1942 IRA Chief of Staff [[Se\u00e1n McCool]] was arrested and imprisoned, and that point the job came to McNamee.<ref name=\"IrishCentral\"/>\n\nHe didn't hold the position long holder, as he was later arrested again, this time in [[Dublin]] on 23 May 1942. He was given a three-year sentence to be served in the [[Curragh]], where he was placed with hundreds of other men from across Ireland who had been arrested for IRA activity by a [[Fianna F\u00e1il]] government determined not to allow the IRA to threaten Ireland's neutrality. During his him in the Curragh he learned [[Gaeilge|Irish]] and [[Spanish language|Spanish]], while he raised the eyebrows of some detainees when he described [[Jesus Christ]] as \"as a revolutionary and a socialist\".<ref name=\"IrishCentral\"/>  It was also during this period that he is believed to have become a [[Trotskyist]] upon conversations with fellow left-wing IRA members in the camp.<ref>{{cite book |last=Bell |first=J. Bowyer |date=1987 |title=The Gun in Politics: Analysis of Irish Political Conflict, 1916-86  |url=https://books.google.ie/books?id=DyEuDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT116&lpg=PT116&dq=Eoin+McNamee+IRA+Trotskyist&source=bl&ots=xOanGYed5s&sig=ACfU3U1twaZve4dhl03Pt-a39wVgMwrqsw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiDoOaCxonmAhUlQRUIHZeUAwgQ6AEwDXoECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=Eoin%20McNamee%20IRA%20Trotskyist&f=false |location= |publisher=Routledge |page= |isbn= |author-link= |quote=Inside the Curragh, Gould not only offered Russian Language classes to the bored but also the ideological temptations of communism. And he began to have some takers and, given the Curragh, some dissenters as ultimately the Trotskyists, including Eoin McNamee (...) outnumbered the Stalinists. Somehow to them Trotsky seemed more anti-imperialist than Stalin.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Treacy |first=Matt |date=2013 |title=The Communist Party of Ireland 1921 - 2011 |url=https://books.google.ie/books?id=DpT2AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA161&lpg=PA161&dq=Eoin+McNamee+IRA+Trotskyist&source=bl&ots=ua6k9y8lF5&sig=ACfU3U1jRhguQRY1VSpQHG1fSYqFs_2REQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiDoOaCxonmAhUlQRUIHZeUAwgQ6AEwDnoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=Eoin%20McNamee%20IRA%20Trotskyist&f=false |location= |publisher= |page=161 |isbn= |author-link= |quote=Boywer Bell claims that Eoin McNamee became a Trotskyist in the Curragh}}</ref>\n\n==Later life==\nFollowing the years spent in the Curragh, McNamee emigrated to the [[United States]]. He moved first to Philadelphia before settling in the Chicago area, where he is supposed to have acted as the go-between for the IRA leadership and its weapons suppliers in the U.S. When the IRA split between [[Official IRA]] and the [[Provisional IRA]] he choose to side with the Provisionals. He was said to be a close friend of fellow IRA gun-runner and left-winger [[George Harrison (Irish Republican)|George Harrison]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Holland|first1=John|title=IRA Puts On A Hard Face|url=http://irishecho.com/2011/02/ira-puts-on-a-hard-face-4/|website=irishecho.com|publisher=irish echo newspaper, Feb 16, 2014|accessdate=19 November 2014|ref=1}}</ref><ref name=\"IrishCentral\"/>\n\nA Sinn F\u00e9in [[cumann]] is named in his honor: Eoin McNamee Cumann, Kildress, Co. Tyrone. A monument to his memory stands at a quiet crossroad in the Sperrin Mountains of his native County Tyrone.\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book|last=English|first=Richard|title=Armed Struggle: The History of the IRA|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K-XsIheKNYIC&pg=PA62|accessdate=29 December 2014|date=2008-09-04|publisher=Pan Macmillan|isbn=9780330475785|pages=62\u2013}}\n*{{cite book|last=Bell|first=J. Bowyer|title=The Gun in Politics: An Analysis of Irish Political Conflict, 1916-1986|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_qQsuhGKDzoC&pg=PA102|accessdate=29 December 2014|date=1987-01-01|publisher=Transaction Publishers|isbn=9781412837132|pages=102\u2013}}\n*{{cite book|last=Treacy|first=Matt|title=The Communist Party of Ireland 1921 - 2011|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DpT2AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA161|accessdate=29 December 2014|year=2012|publisher=Lulu.com|isbn=9781291093186|pages=161\u2013}}\n*{{cite book|last=Hull|first=Mark M.|title=Irish Secrets: German Espionage in Ireland, 1939-45|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wjFnAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=29 December 2014|date=January 2003|publisher=Irish Academic Press|isbn=9780716527565}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{ATIRA}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSOR